    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_751858127" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/751858127" />
    <a title="Mark" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10645941-mark"><img alt="Mark" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1341276324p2/10645941.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/751858127?book_show_action=true">Oct 29, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark" href="/user/show/10645941-mark">Mark</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781876485030" href="/book/show/3928049-the-mystery-of-a-hansom-cab">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10645941-mark?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer751858127" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2304276232780898636">This book contains a great little story that moves along at a fast pace, despite being written back in the 1880s. I&apos;m living in inner Melbourne, so this book is a little special to me - it is amazing how many of the locations still carry the same mood and feeling that Fergus Hume evokes in his book. Although Little Bourke Street is no longer seedy, it is easy to imagine the poverty and shady deals that would have taken place in the narrow laneways that still exist in this part of Melbourne today</span>
  <span id="freeText2304276232780898636" style="display:none">This book contains a great little story that moves along at a fast pace, despite being written back in the 1880s. I'm living in inner Melbourne, so this book is a little special to me - it is amazing how many of the locations still carry the same mood and feeling that Fergus Hume evokes in his book. Although Little Bourke Street is no longer seedy, it is easy to imagine the poverty and shady deals that would have taken place in the narrow laneways that still exist in this part of Melbourne today. East Melbourne is still posh, and Fitzroy Gardens are still spooky when used as a short cut to walk home late at night.<br /><br />The character development is good and you get a good feel for the lifestyle of the rich and famous at a time when Melbourne was growing quickly as a result of the gold rush. The women are particularly strong characters - they are critical to the most interesting elements of the plot. We also get a pretty graphic account of life for people stuck in poverty - nothing much changes over the ages. <br /><br />Hume also writes in a very clever tone where there is an under current of social criticism and sarcasm that still connects with modern day readers. One particularly amusing account of a shopping trip by one of the women characters was particularly relevant to current time: "After Madge had purchased a dozen articles she did not want, and had interviewed her dressmaker on the momentous subject of a new dress, she remembered that Brian was waiting for her,and hurried quickly to the door."<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2304276232780898636" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


